According to structural and numerical analysis, M. theseus scale architectures have various tubular characteristics with different helix degrees, twining forms, and orientations. In addition, the period and VF are also in disordered distributions. The multiple morphologies of the tubular forms, periods, and VFs lead to diversity in the reflection bands and intensities. From the macroscopic view, the scales appear bright white. For tubular form difference characterization, coefficients A, B, and C are introduced in the gyroid model as5A⋅sinxcosy+B⋅sinycosz+C⋅sinzcosx=tt≥a\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
